{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6a2d996b-38cf-4812-a554-25898ebb2ec4","content":"This repo doesn't contain docs on this topic, but here's the general guidance for macOS:\n\n### Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** — macOS disables them by default:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Set the core dump directory** (cores go to `/cores/` by default):\n   ```bash\n   ls /cores/\n   ```\n\n3. **Reproduce the crash** — run your NativeAOT app. macOS will write a Mach-O core file to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n4. **If `/cores/` is empty**, check that SIP (System Integrity Protection) isn't blocking core dumps. You may need to:\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n   ```\n\n5. **Analyze the dump** with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n6. **Also check Console.app** or `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` — macOS often writes `.crash` report files there automatically, which contain stack traces and register state.\n\n> **Key difference for NativeAOT**: Since there's no `createdump` (it ships with CoreCLR, not NativeAOT), you rely entirely on the OS-level core dump facility. The `lldb` workflow replaces the managed `dotnet-dump` workflow.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b6694d4e-c018-4300-984a-ff467b92e16c","outputTokens":353,"requestId":"640F:131578:15AE056:192E0BB:69EC1A1D"},"id":"d60c75a6-5cb7-48ca-8238-85953246256f","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:34:30.679Z","parentId":"3a9baeb4-36e9-45af-8a5c-62117aa80b67"}
